        "answer": "```\nLet's assume we shade cell r5c4.\n\nAccording to the Connectivity Rule, every unshaded cell must be connected to all other unshaded cells through adjacent (up, down, left, or right) unshaded cells. For cell r4c4 to stay connected, at least one of its neighboring cells\u2014r3c4, r4c3, r4c5, or r5c4\u2014must remain unshaded.\n\nHowever, we already know that r3c4, r4c3, and r4c5 are shaded. This leaves only r5c4 as the possible cell to keep connectivity for r4c4.\n\nBut this directly contradicts our assumption that r5c4 is shaded. Therefore, our initial assumption must be wrong.\n\nHence, r5c4 **must remain unshaded** to satisfy the Connectivity Rule and ensure that all unshaded cells are connected.\n```",
